3.2	Introduction
The internship at Besant Technology covered two major domains: Full Stack Web Development and Quality Assurance Testing. The primary objective was to develop functional web applications using modern technologies while ensuring quality through rigorous testing methodologies.
Full Stack Development involves creating both client-facing (frontend) and server-side (backend) components of a web application. The frontend was built using React.js while Node.js with Express.js was used for backend development, communicating with MySQL and MongoDB databases.
The internship at Besant Technology was structured to provide a holistic learning experience covering the full spectrum of software development and quality assurance processes. The learning journey began with an orientation week where interns were introduced to the company’s work culture, internal tools, coding standards, and expectations. This initial phase was crucial for setting the foundation for productive work throughout the internship.
Full Stack Development, as practiced at Besant Technology, is not merely about writing code for the frontend and backend in isolation. It involves an integrated understanding of how user interfaces communicate with server-side logic, how data is persisted and retrieved from databases, how authentication and authorization mechanisms protect system resources, and how the entire application is deployed and maintained in a production environment.
The React.js frontend development training emphasized the component-based architecture that is central to modern web development. Each component was designed to be reusable, testable, and composable. React hooks such as useState, useEffect, useContext, and custom hooks were used extensively to manage component lifecycle and state without relying on class-based components. State management across the application was handled using the Redux toolkit, enabling predictable state transitions and easy debugging. How the entire application is deployed and maintained in a production environment. Each component was designed to be reusable, testable, and composable. React hooks such as use State, that is
 
central to modern web development. Each component was designed to be reusable and testable. State management across the application was handled using the Redux toolkit, enabling predictable state.
The Node.js backend training covered the Express.js framework in depth, including how to define routes, implement middleware functions, handle errors globally, and structure the application using the MVC (Model-View-Controller) pattern. RESTful API design principles were followed rigorously, including proper use of HTTP methods, status codes, and response payloads. Input validation was performed using the express-validator library to ensure data integrity at the API layer.
Database design and management formed an integral part of the backend development curriculum. For relational data, MySQL was used with schema design principles including normalization, foreign key constraints, and indexing for performance optimization. For document-based data, MongoDB was used, leveraging its flexible schema to handle hierarchical and unstructured data efficiently. Both databases were accessed via ORM/ODM libraries — Sequelize for MySQL and Mongoose for MongoDB — enabling clean and maintainable data access code.
