3.4	System Design
The system followed a three-tier architecture comprising the Presentation Layer (React.js), Application Layer (Node.js/Express.js), and Data Layer (MySQL/MongoDB). This modular architecture ensured separation of concerns and made the system easier to maintain and test.
The frontend communicated with the backend via RESTful APIs using HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE). Authentication was handled using JSON Web Tokens (JWT), validated on every protected route.




Fig3.1 Three System Architecture

The three-tier architecture chosen for this project is a well-established pattern in enterprise software development. In this model, each tier has a clearly defined responsibility and communicates with adjacent tiers through well-defined interfaces. This separation of concerns reduces coupling between components, making the system easier to develop, test, maintain, and scale independently.The Presentation Layer, built with React.js, manages all user interface rendering and user interaction handling. It uses client-side routing with React Router to enable single-page application (SPA) navigation without full page reloads. The application state is managed using Redux, with asynchronous operations
 
The Application Layer, developed with Node.js and Express.js, serves as the brain of the system. It receives HTTP requests from the frontend, validates inputs, processes business logic, and delegates data operations to the appropriate database. The layer is structured into multiple modules including User, Product, Order, Authentication, and Report, each encapsulated in its own controller, service.
The Data Layer comprises both MySQL and MongoDB databases, each serving distinct data storage needs. MySQL stores structured relational data such as user accounts, product inventory, and order records. MongoDB stores semi-structured data such as audit logs, activity feeds, and configuration settings. Both databases are connected to the application layer via respective ORM and ODM libraries, providing abstracted and type-safe data access methods.
The system also incorporates a caching layer using Redis, which stores frequently accessed data such as user session tokens, product catalog listings, and configuration parameters. This significantly reduces the load on primary databases and improves response times for read-heavy endpoints. Data Layer comprises both MySQL and MongoDB databases, each serving distinct data storage needs. MySQL stores structured relational data such as user accounts, product inventory, and order records. MongoDB stores semi-structured data such as audit logs, activity feeds, and configuration settings. Both databases are connected to the application layer via respective ORM and ODM libraries
