3.5	Implementation

3.5.1	Full Stack Development
The Full Stack Development phase involved building a complete web application from scratch. The frontend was developed using React.js with reusable component-based architecture, including login/registration pages, dashboard, and data management views. The system also incorporates a caching layer using Redis, which stores frequently accessed data such as user session tokens, product catalogue listings, and configuration parameters. This significantly reduces the load on primary databases and improves response times for read-heavy endpoints. Authentication was implemented using JSON Web Tokens (JWT). Upon successful login, the backend generated a signed access token (valid for 15 minutes) and a refresh token (valid for 7 days). The access token was stored in memory on the frontend (not in localStorage, to prevent XSS), while the refresh token was stored in an HTTP-only cookie to protect

Fig 3.2 Full Stack Technology Stack Used During Internship
In Fig 3.2 The development process followed a feature-branch workflow on GitHub. Each new feature was developed in a dedicated branch, reviewed by the mentor through a pull request, and merged into the main branch only after approval. This practice enforced code quality and provided interns with experience in a professional development workflow.
The React.js frontend was organized into a modular folder structure: components for reusable UI elements, pages for route-level views, services for API communication, store for Redux state management, utils for helper functions, and hooks for custom React hooks. This organization made the codebase navigable and maintainable, even as it grew in size and complexity.
 
Authentication was implemented using JSON Web Tokens (JWT). Upon successful login, the backend generated a signed access token (valid for 15 minutes) and a refresh token (valid for 7 days). The access token was stored in memory on the frontend (not in localStorage, to prevent XSS), while the refresh token was stored in an HTTP-only cookie to protect against cross-site scripting attacks. Token refresh was handled automatically through an Axios interceptor, providing a seamless user experience.
The database schema for MySQL was designed with proper normalization up to the Third Normal Form (3NF) to eliminate data redundancy. Indexes were created on frequently queried columns such as email, user_id, and created_at to optimize read performance. Transactions were used for operations involving multiple tables to ensure data consistency and integrity. Token refresh was handled automatically through. Token refresh was handled automatically through an Axios interceptor, providing a seamless user HTTP-only cookie to protect against cross-site scripting attacks. Token refresh was handled automatically
