3.5.2	QA Testing
The QA Testing phase involved comprehensive testing of the developed application. Manual test cases were written for each feature and executed systematically. Automated test scripts were written using Selenium for end-to-end browser testing and Jest for unit and integration testing.



Fig 3.3 QA Testing Process Flow
The QA Testing phase was conducted systematically across four stages: Unit Testing, Integration Testing, System Testing, and User Acceptance Testing (UAT). Each stage had clearly defined objectives, test cases, and entry/exit criteria, ensuring a structured and comprehensive quality assurance process.
Unit Testing was performed at the component and function level using Jest. Individual React components were tested using React Testing Library, which allows testing of components in a manner that simulates actual user interactions. For backend functions, Jest mocks were used to isolate units from their dependencies, such as database queries and external API calls, enabling fast and reliable tests.
 
Integration Testing verified that different modules of the application worked correctly when combined. API endpoints were tested using Postman collections, with pre-request scripts setting up test data and test scripts validating response payloads, status codes, and headers. These Postman tests were also automated and run as part of the CI/CD pipeline using Newman, Postman’s CLI companion.
System Testing encompassed end-to-end testing of complete user workflows using Selenium WebDriver with Java. Test scripts were written for critical user journeys including user registration, login, product browsing, cart management, order placement, and order status tracking. These tests were parameterized using Excel data sheets, enabling data-driven testing with multiple input combinations. These Postman tests were also automated and run as part of the CI/CD pipeline using Newman
Bug tracking was performed systematically using JIRA. Each defect identified during testing was logged with detailed information including steps to reproduce, expected behavior, actual behavior, severity, priority, and attachments (screenshots or logs). A formal bug lifecycle was followed: Open → Assigned
→ In Progress → Fixed → Retest → Closed.

