3.5.2.1	Test Planning and Strategy
The QA testing strategy for the project was documented in a formal Test Plan that outlined the testing objectives, scope, approach, resources, schedule, and risk assessment. The test plan was reviewed and approved by the Technical Lead before testing commenced, ensuring alignment between the development and QA teams on quality expectations and exit criteria. Regression testing was performed at the end of each sprint to ensure that new features did not break previously working functionality. A regression test suite comprising the most critical and frequently.
Test cases were documented in a structured format using Excel spreadsheets shared on Google Drive, with each test case containing a unique identifier, the associated requirement ID, preconditions, test steps, test data, expected results, and status fields for tracking execution results. A separate sheet was maintained for defect tracking until JIRA was formally integrated into the workflow. The test plan was reviewed and approved by the Technical Lead before testing commenced, ensuring alignment between the development.
Regression testing was performed at the end of each sprint to ensure that new features did not break previously working functionality. A regression test suite comprising the most critical and frequently used test cases was maintained and updated with each sprint, providing a reliable safety net against regressions introduced during active development. The test plan was reviewed and approved by the Technical Lead.
3.5.2.2	Automated Testing with Selenium
The Selenium-based automation framework was structured using the Page Object Model (POM) design pattern, which separates the test logic from the UI element locators and interactions. Each web page in the application had a corresponding Page Object class that encapsulated the page’s elements and the actions that could be performed on them. Test classes then called these Page Object methods to drive the browser, making tests readable and maintainable.
ChromeDriver was used as the WebDriver implementation, with headless Chrome configured for CI/CD environments to enable test execution without a graphical browser. Test execution reports were generated using ExtentReports, providing HTML reports with pass/fail status, execution time, screenshots on failure, and trend charts showing test results across multiple runs. Test classes then called these Page Object methods to drive the browser, making tests readable and maintainable.
 
