4.1.1	Technical Achievements
From a purely technical standpoint, the internship resulted in the delivery of a production-ready web application that passed all acceptance criteria defined at the project’s inception. The application supported concurrent access by up to 50 simultaneous users without degradation in performance, as validated through JMeter load testing. All critical and high-severity defects were resolved prior to the final project handover, with only one medium-severity defect deferred to the next development iteration due to scope constraints.
The codebase produced during the internship comprised approximately 8,500 lines of JavaScript code (excluding comments and blank lines) distributed across the frontend and backend. The code adhered to established style guides (Airbnb JavaScript Style Guide for React, and the Express.js best practices guide for the backend), validated through ESLint configuration integrated into the CI/CD pipeline. Code coverage for unit tests reached 78%, exceeding the initial target of 70%. All critical and high-severity defects were resolved prior to the final project handover, with only one medium-severity defect deferred to the next development iteration due to scope constraints. The application supported concurrent access by up to 50 simultaneous users without degradation in performance.
 
4.1.2	Professional Development
Beyond technical deliverables, the internship fostered significant professional development. Participation in Agile ceremonies — sprint planning, daily stand-ups, sprint reviews, and retrospectives — provided firsthand experience of how high-performing software teams operate. Contributing to sprint retrospectives offered the opportunity to reflect critically on processes and suggest improvements, a practice that instills a culture of continuous improvement.
Presenting technical findings and project progress to senior team members during sprint reviews developed the ability to communicate complex technical concepts to mixed audiences. Writing detailed bug reports in JIRA, with precise steps to reproduce, severity assessments, and supporting evidence, honed analytical thinking and documentation skills that are directly applicable to a professional QA or development role.
The internship also highlighted the importance of time management and task prioritization in a deadline-driven environment. Balancing multiple concurrent tasks — feature development, writing test cases, fixing reported bugs, and attending team meetings — required disciplined time allocation and clear communication of blockers to the mentor. These experiences formed the foundation of a professional work ethic that will serve well throughout a career in software engineering.
