4.2	Key Learnings
•	Proficiency in React.js component lifecycle, hooks, and state management.
•	Hands-on experience with RESTful API development using Node.js and Express.js.
•	Understanding of database design for both SQL (MySQL) and NoSQL (MongoDB) databases.
•	Mastery of testing methodologies including manual, automation, and API testing.
•	Experience with Agile methodology, sprint planning, and team collaboration.
The internship reinforced the understanding that software development is not a solitary activity but a collaborative process. Effective communication, whether through daily stand-ups, code review comments, bug reports, or sprint retrospectives, is as important as technical skill. The ability to articulate ideas, ask precise questions, and document findings clearly emerged as a critical professional competency developed during this internship.
Version control discipline was another major learning. The internship enforced the use of meaningful commit messages following the Conventional Commits specification (e.g., feat: add user registration endpoint, fix: resolve JWT expiry bug). This practice, combined with branch naming conventions and structured pull request descriptions, made the project’s change history meaningful and navigable.
Exposure to CI/CD pipelines through Jenkins and GitHub Actions was an eye-opening experience. Understanding how code changes automatically trigger builds, run test suites, and deploy to staging environments illustrated the power of automation in modern software delivery. Configuring the pipeline to fail builds on test failures or code coverage drops below threshold instilled the habit of writing tests alongside feature code.
The experience of working with both SQL and NoSQL databases in a single project provided a nuanced understanding of when to use which type of storage. This technical decision-making ability, grounded in practical experience, is a differentiator in job interviews and real-world project assessments.
